instruction: [INST] Analyze this file to learn MacBook motherboard repair. The 'definitions' section explains key technical terms. The 'threads' section contains real-world repair discussions. Use both sections to understand and learn how to troubleshoot MacBook issues. Posts from username 'larossmann' , 'dukefawks' , and '2informaticos' are posts from trusted experts.[/INST]

definitions.820-3536: What is 820-3536? a LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER.
definitions.PP5V_S5: What is PP5V_S5? This is a 5v power rail that is present when the machine is in an S5 soft off state..
definitions.PP5V_S4: What is PP5V_S4? PP5V_S4 is a 5v power rail present when the machine is in an S4 suspend to disk state..
definitions.U6100: What is U6100? this is an SPI ROM chip that holds the BIOS which is necessary for the machine to POST or try and power on..
definitions.PPVRTC_G3H: What is PPVRTC_G3H? PPVRTC_G3H is a 3.3v power rail for the RTC circuit present when the machine is in a G3H global system hardware off state. .
definitions.ADAPTER_EN: What is ADAPTER_EN? SMC_ADAPTER_EN enables the machine to work off of the power adapter when the proper power adapter is attached. Attacching an 85w Macbook Pro 15” power adapter to a 13” Macbook that requires a 60w power adapter is ok, attaching a 45w Macbook Air power adapter to a 15” macbook Pro that needs an 85w power adapter will result in SMC_ADAPTER_EN missing. .
definitions.PP5V_S0: What is PP5V_S0? PP5V_S0 is a 5v power rail present when the system is in an S0 working state..
definitions.U1950: What is U1950? This chip often becomes corroded on pin 8 on the PP3V42_G3H pin causing PM_SLP_S4_L to go missing.
definitions.PPVCC_S0_CPU: What is PPVCC_S0_CPU? The "PPVCC_S0_CPU" power rail is responsible for supplying power to the CPU when the MacBook is fully on, or in the S0 state. This rail is one of the main voltages that the CPU requires for operation. .

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3536</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-a wont turn on
threads.message: I have an <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3536</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-a macbook pro retina, I get an amber light on the charger, but the computer wont turn on, I am missing <SIGNAL>PP5V_S4</SIGNAL>, <SIGNAL>PP5V_S5</SIGNAL> is presant. board was water damaged, thanks for any help

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3536</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-a wont turn on
threads.message:
Check if <SIGNAL>PP5V_S4</SIGNAL> is pulsing, you may need an oscilloscope, pulses are pretty fast and DMM may not catch it....

Also check for water damage around <CHIP>U6100</CHIP> and <CHIP>U1900</CHIP>...

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3536</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-a wont turn on
threads.message: as far as i can tell <SIGNAL>PP5V_S4</SIGNAL> isnt pulsing, but i dont have an oscilloscope. there was some blue along the 1-4 pin side of <CHIP>U1900</CHIP> and the ground pin of <CHIP>U6100</CHIP> had some aswell

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3536</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-a wont turn on
threads.message: check the traces between the resistors around <CHIP>U6100</CHIP> and the CPU

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3536</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-a wont turn on
threads.message: The only area that seems to have bad traces are the probe points on the pins 1-4 side of <CHIP>U8330</CHIP>

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3536</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-a wont turn on
threads.message: Look up all the termination resistors in the data lines of <CHIP>U6100</CHIP> and check them all. Also check continuity between them all. I think there are 16 of them.

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3536</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-a wont turn on
threads.message: the only resistor that i found that was not what the schematic said was <RESISTOR>R6131</RESISTOR>, resistance was 77k ohms but theres no resistor on the board there; and its also not labled "no stuff"

threads.message: Yeah, there is your problem. Check around <CHIP>U1900</CHIP>, usually corroded pins or dead. Also check resistance to GND on PPVRTC rail.

threads.message:
Most likely bad CPU and this is junk.

Sometimes it is a short that can be worked around, such as in this case: fast forward to 1:30:00 to see me fix a case of 0 ohms to ground on a board with shorted <SIGNAL>PPVRTC_G3H</SIGNAL> that is very similar to yours. 

[url]https://youtu.be/RtHRwZxvjME?t=5434[/url]

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3536</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-a wont turn on
threads.message: There is a few caps on the PPVRTC line to GND. Take them all off, if there still is a short the CPU is dead.

threads.message: Check carefully for power cycling on the 5V bus L7520. PPBUS present at 12.6V? 3V at L7560?

threads.message: Well, I'm running out out ideas here. If there is no short on L7520 to GND it should power up and pulse at least. Could be corrosion under SMC or a dead CPU at this point.

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3536</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-a wont turn on
threads.message: I doubt the chip is dead. Usually the traces or resistors are corroded. Yes without a functioning <CHIP>U6100</CHIP> the board will power cycle. Pull <CHIP>U6100</CHIP> and read it on the programmer, do not loose the original dump!

threads.title: <LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>820-3536</LOGIC BOARD PART NUMBER>-a wont turn on
threads.message: Buy a TL866. Pre programmed usually is a dump from another board and ME region will be fucked. Get a donor board, you need those anyway.
